05094nam a22008415i 9780812291445DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)972175123  a97808122914457 a10.9783/97808122914452doi  a(DE-B1597)451289  a(OCoLC)952807628  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL1080202bisacsh04a275.6/032231 aPenn, Michael Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnvisioning Islam :bSyriac Christians and the Early Muslim World /cMichael Philip Penn. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDivinations: Rereading Late Ancient Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. When Good Things Happened to Other People: Syriac Memories of the Islamic Conquests -- tChapter 2. A Different Type of Difference- Making: Syriac Narratives of Religious Identity -- tChapter 3. Using Muslims to Think With: Narratives of Islamic Rulers -- tChapter 4. Blurring Boundaries: The Continuum Between Early Christianity and Early Islam -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first Christians to encounter Islam were not Latin-speakers from the western Mediterranean or Greek-speakers from Constantinople but Mesopotamian Christians who spoke the Aramaic dialect of Syriac. Under Muslim rule from the seventh century onward, Syriac Christians wrote the most extensive descriptions extant of early Islam. Seldom translated and often omitted from modern historical reconstructions, this vast body of texts reveals a complicated and evolving range of religious and cultural exchanges that took place from the seventh to the ninth century.The first book-length analysis of these earliest encounters, Envisioning Islam highlights the ways these neglected texts challenge the modern scholarly narrative of early Muslim conquests, rulers, and religious practice. Examining Syriac sources including letters, theological tracts, scientific treatises, and histories, Michael Philip Penn reveals a culture of substantial interreligious interaction in which the categorical boundaries between Christianity and Islam were more ambiguous than distinct. The diversity of ancient Syriac images of Islam, he demonstrates, revolutionizes our understanding of the early Islamic world and challenges widespread cultural assumptions about the history of exclusively hostile Christian-Muslim relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristianity and other religionsvIslamxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslamxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aIslamvRelationsvChristianityxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSyriac ChristiansxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aSyriac ChristiansxHistoryyTo 1500yTo 1500. 0aSyriac ChristiansxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Christian Church / History.2bisacsh  aAncient Studies.  aHistory.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2015z9783110438727oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229144540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812291445423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812291445.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d201